				"This very good all-in-one computer would be a great choice for an instant videoconferencing computer during a quarantine. \n\nPROS\n-Very simple setup and go. Just plug in the power cable, mouse, and keyboard. Then connect to wifi or ethernet and you on your way. \n-Very compact form factor. It takes up no more depth space than a typical monitor.The computer is neatly located on the back of the monitor and you wouldn't even know it's there.  \n-Monitor bezels are very thin creating a sleek minimalist appearance. \n-Resolution is 1920x1080 which is fine for a monitor this size. \n-Can run a 2nd monitor via HDMI so you can run a 2 monitor setup. I hooked mine up to a 4k monitor and it works well. \n-Computer specs are excellent with a fast NVMe ssd. The 8gb of RAM is plenty for most applications.-Integrated card reader and optical drive add flexibility and convenience. \n-Integrated webcam is especially useful for video conferencing during pandemics. There is a small slider at the top that physically closes the camera for privacy. \n\nCONS\n-Stand only tilts. No height or swivel. \n-No VESA mounting option. \n-There is a power brick which adds clutter. Since one of the main reasons to get an AIO is to decrease clutter, the power brick is disappointing.  \n\nOTHER\n-McAfee virus protect is preinstalled and within a day it was showing pop-ups on the desktop. Unless you really want this app, uninstall it right away. There were no other 3rd party preloaded apps which is nice. \n-Speakers sound fine but I wish they pointed outwards toward you instead of downward. \n-4 USB ports which may or may not be enough although you can always add a USB hub. No USB-C which is slightly disappointing since this is 2020.\n-Included wired keyboard is fine but the wired mouse is cheap. I'm glad they went cheap on these accessories because many people will just add on a wireless set anyway. \n\nOVERALL\nThis is an impressive all-in-one (AIO) computer with a form factor so sleek, you wouldn't even know a computer is hidden behind the monitor. I've built over 10 computers in my life including the small form factor NUC's and can say that the specs on this Lenovo are a tremendous value at under 600 dollars. \n\nLike any AIO computer, you can't upgrade the monitor and you can't expect to upgrade the SSD or RAM. Fortunately, this Lenovo minimizes those issues by allowing you to run a 2nd monitor (even 4k) and using a blazing 256gb NVMe drive which would work excellent as a boot drive for a long time. You can always add an external USB hard drive if you need more storage.",
